\begin_layout Standard
Once all the corrections are performed as well as possible, it is time to
 extract an activation energy and a prefactor for each platinum spot.
 The point of the experiment is to see how small the spot can be and still
 withhold a constant activation energy and a prefactor linear dependent
 on the spot area.
 To do this, we fit the data to the the Arrhenius equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=Ae^{-E_{a}/k_{b}T}
\]

\end_inset

which will give activation energy as well as the prefactor.
 The fitting is performed by a small python script which takes data from
 the CINF database and fits the data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mass spectrometer calibration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A mass spectrometer does not measure the ion current directly, but measures
 the signal after it has passed through the Secondary Electron Multiplier
 (SEM).
 The amplification on the SEM is of course heavily dependent on the voltage
 across the dynodes but unfortunately it also depends on many other factors
 such as the oxidation state of the SEM as well mass of the impeding molecule.
 On top of this, the mass filter itself is also not guaranteed to have a
 fixed transmission efficiency across the entire measuring range.
 All these factors means that it is highly difficult to estimate the absolute
 yield of a given molecule, only the indirect quantity, SEM current, is
 truly known.
 However, it is not impossible to make at least an rough estimate of the
 amplification factor, as long as one remembers that the values should not
 be considered very accurate.
 Looking at Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sensitivity_co2_background"

\end_inset

, it is evident that the conversion at 140
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

min is zero, and thus the combined signal of the O
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and CO should correspond to the nominal flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times10^{14}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

molecules/s, since no other molecules are leaving the reactor.
 Reading off the figure tells us that the measured currents for O
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 and CO, respectively, are 69.4
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

nA and 25.5
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

nA.
 This means that as a first approximation we can estimate the SEM amplification
 to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{SEM}\approx\frac{\left(69.4+25.5\right)\,\mbox{nA}}{6\times10^{14}\,\mbox{molecules/s}}=\frac{1.6\times10^{-13}\,\mbox{nA}}{\mbox{molecule/s}}=\frac{1.6\times10^{-13}\,\mbox{C}}{\mbox{molecule}}
\]

\end_inset

Incidentally it is worth noticing that this value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{SEM}$
\end_inset

 is quite close to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{6}$
\end_inset

 times the elementary charge, which is the typical rule of thumb for the
 amplification factor for an average SEM.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{SEM}$
\end_inset

 was estimated from sample N8 and so this will also be the sample which
 will be defined to have a flow 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times10^{14}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

molecules/s at room temperature.
 With this estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{SEM}$
\end_inset

 we can make a plot with approximate absolute numbers on both axis.
 
\end_layout

